     Of course, Hollywood can show any fantasy it likes, but this was not really a fantasy in the same sense that interstellar travel and transporter beams would be. Screenwriter Arthur C. Clarke was, and still is, a grand visionary; but he is also a hard-headed scientist and engineer. His vision of 2001 was based on what he believed was realistically possible. Nothing portrayed in 2001 was beyond the likely state of the art as it seemed in the mid-60s. Indeed, the vision is fairly conservative in many respects. <br>
     Clarke is not now an advocate of nuclear propulsion in space, but it is hard to see how his vision could have been realized without it. This was implicit in much long-term space planning during the 1960s, including most of the ideas incorporated in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 2001</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. During Project Apollo, NASA worked on a plan for a Mars landing in the early 1980s. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/craft/marsusa.htm"> Mars USA</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. This called for NERVA derived nuclear upper stage for an improved Saturn V rocket. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/stages/satv25su.htm"> Nuclear S-V</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. This would effectively multiply the effectiveness of the basic moon landing technology to the point where a Mars landing could have been accomplished as an immediate follow-on. <br>
      The Soviet Union had plans that were, if anything, more ambitious: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/articles/aelita.htm">Aelita:Soviet Mars Projects</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Nuclear power was essential to these efforts. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/articles/sovctric.htm">Soviet nuclear-electric to Mars</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/articles/sovermal.htm">Soviet nuclear-thermal to Mars</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
Improvements in nuclear-thermal technology, in particular, make these ambitious plans more feasible than ever. <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/props/nucarlh2.htm"> LH-2 nuclear engines</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.astronautix.com/engines/timind75.htm"> timberwind 75</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. What is missing is political will, and public education to counter the dominant tide of luddite druidism.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/30/01 8:11:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=101.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: 2001: No Space Odyssey</span><hr size=1> I was just thinking about that today! (go figure)...<br>
