Not being clairvoyant, I cannot really tell what was in Arthur Clarke's mind. I can, however, infer what he would have believed was possible. There was nothing important in the movie that a well-informed observer in 1966-67(which Clarke certainly was) would not have regarded as reasonably achievable by 2001. By the time of the first moon landings in 1969, NASA was working on a plan to use NERVA derived upper stages to send humans to Mars by 1982. This same propulsion technology would have made earth-orbit/lunar shuttle operations simple and routine, routine enough to build up a very large base within the given timeframe. Keep in mind that 2001 was over 30 years after the first landings, and this was foreseeable in the mid-60s. The pinwheel space station depended on economical <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  fully reusable</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> shuttles that also seemed reasonably close and feasible by the mid-60s. Only the post-Apollo cutbacks prevented such a shuttle from being built. It wouldn't even have needed nuclear power, though this could have been made available given the will. The ramjet (apparently) shuttle in the movie is more speculative and probably could not have been achieved, knowing what we know now. The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Discovery's</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> propulsion isn't unambiguously specified and fusion was not achieved by 2001, but an advanced NERVA or NEP system could have done the job and these were fairly certain when the movie was conceived.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 7/4/02 3:11:52 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 607<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/8/02 10:37:52 am)</font><br>   <